INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b41b90c0-2363-4da4-b926-0cd93e882760',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Integration Testing — Mocking at the Right Boundary$escape$,
  $escape$Integration tests in Cypress shine when you test multiple components wired together — a form, its validation logic, and the submission handler — without mocking every internal detail. The key is mocking at the network boundary, not at the component level. Use `cy.intercept()` to stub HTTP calls and let your real components render, interact, and respond naturally.

A common mistake is over-mocking: stubbing child components or internal state, which turns your integration test into a glorified unit test. Instead, mount the parent component with `cy.mount()`, let it render its children, and only intercept the outbound API call. This validates the full render tree, event delegation, and state propagation.

Set `cy.intercept()` before `cy.mount()` so the stub is registered before any requests fire. Use `cy.wait('@alias')` to assert the request payload — confirming your components assembled the correct data before sending it. This boundary-at-the-network pattern gives you high confidence without brittle, over-mocked tests.$escape$,
  $escape$it('submits assembled form data to the API', () => {
  cy.intercept('POST', '/api/login', { statusCode: 200, body: { token: 'abc' } }).as('loginRequest');

  cy.mount(<LoginForm />);

  cy.get('[data-cy=email]').type('dev@example.com');
  cy.get('[data-cy=password]').type('secret123');
  cy.get('[data-cy=submit]').click();

  cy.wait('@loginRequest').its('request.body').should('deep.equal', {
    email: 'dev@example.com',
    password: 'secret123',
  });
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
