INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5f32005a-a616-433f-a79a-d9eca4bdf017',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Test Data Management — Factories, Fixtures, and Seeding State$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress fixtures (`cy.fixture()`) are great for static snapshots, but they break down when tests need varied or relational data. The fix: factory functions paired with `cy.task()` for server-side seeding.

Define a factory in `cypress/support/factories/user.ts` that returns a typed object with sensible defaults, accepting a partial override. Call `cy.task('seedUser', userFactory({ role: 'admin' }))` to push that record into your test database before the spec runs. Your `cypress.config.ts` registers the task using a DB client — Prisma, Knex, or raw `pg` — so the data is real, not mocked.

For read-only contract data (dropdown options, static config), `cy.fixture('plans.json')` remains the right tool. Use `fixture` as an alias with `.as()` so the data is reachable across hooks: `cy.fixture('plans').as('plans')` then `cy.get('@plans')` in the test body.

Clean up with an `afterEach` task that truncates seeded tables by a test-run ID injected at factory build time. This keeps runs idempotent without full DB resets between every spec.$escape$,
  $escape$// cypress/support/factories/user.ts
export const userFactory = (overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User => ({
  id: crypto.randomUUID(),
  email: `test+${Date.now()}@example.com`,
  role: 'viewer',
  testRunId: Cypress.env('TEST_RUN_ID'),
  ...overrides,
});

// In your spec
beforeEach(() => {
  cy.task('seedUser', userFactory({ role: 'admin' })).as('adminUser');
});

afterEach(() => {
  cy.task('cleanupTestRun', Cypress.env('TEST_RUN_ID'));
});$escape$,
